3rd Overall Prize; 
1st Prize in Communication and Social Awareness;
1st Prize in Sustainability;
2nd Prize in Energy Efficiency;
2nd Prize in Engineering & Construction.

The Solar Decathlon is an international competition to design and build an energy independent solar house.  Part of the Prêt-à-Loger team, finalist with other 19 European university-teams I worked as engineer in the Design Team. The 18 month work culminated with the construction of the designed sustainable house in Versailles in June and July 2014.For this edition of the Solar Decathlon, the Sustainable City Village- En France, our team won:

profile_positions.description:
My work consisted in:
- Researching Zero Energy opportunities in already refurbished buildings;
- Performing economical evaluation of sustainable refurbishment of office buildings;
- Investigating the business case for Zero Energy refurbishment of commercial buildings.

- Supervising Multicultural project workshops to help new international students to integrate with culturally different study environment;
- Lecturing students about Communication and Presentation techniques;
- Organization of the City Rally for more than 1000 students to help them getting familiar with the history, culture, services and facilities of Delft and its university.

Investigation and evaluation of the effect of retrofitting of the old type house 'The Blue House' .

The Blue House is part of NEES project (Natural Energy Efficiency and Sustainability) included in the Northern Periphery Programme in collaboration with the Arctic Technology Center (ARTEK).
My work consisted in:
- Performance and evaluation of technical measurements such as Blower Door Tests and Thermography;
- Assessment of the results of monitoring works of Carbon dioxide production, relative humidity and temperature;
- Improvement of Low Energy Design in extreme weather conditions; 
- Study and research of architectural parameters to apply in Arctic dwellings.
